Wash and dry produce. Peel and mince or grate @garlic{1%clove}(minced). Thinly slice @scallions{2}(thinly sliced), separating whites from greens. Zest and quarter @lemon{1}(zested and quartered). Trim and dice @mini cucumber{1}(trimmed and diced).

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%tsp} in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Add half the garlic and half the @Turkish spice blend{1%tbsp}; cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add @bulgur wheat{1/2%cup}, @water{1%cup}, @salt{} and @pepper{}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until water has absorbed and bulgur is tender, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat (you'll finish it in Step 5).

In a #small bowl{}, combine scallion whites, half the scallion greens (save the rest for another use), half the lemon zest, 1 TBSP @olive oil{4%tsp}, juice from one lemon wedge, and remaining garlic to taste. Taste and season with a pinch of salt and pepper.

Pat @barramundi{10%oz}(dry) dry with #paper towels{}; season all over with salt and pepper.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large, preferably #nonstick pan{}, over medium-high heat. Add barramundi, skin sides down, and cook until skin is crispy, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Flip and cook until barramundi is cooked through, ~{2-3%minutes} more. Transfer to a paper-towel-lined #plate{}.

When bulgur is done cooking, stir cucumber, half the @feta cheese{1/2%cup}, and a drizzle of olive oil into #pot{}. Taste and season with salt and pepper if desired.

Divide bulgur and barramundi between shallow #bowls{}. Spoon scallion relish over barramundi and garnish with remaining lemon zest to taste. Serve with remaining lemon wedges on the side.

> Barramundi is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.